{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "A Slater determinant is fully specified by its one-body density matrix 24 P ab = ⟨ĉ † b ĉa ⟩, which is Hermitian (P † = P), idempotent (P 2 = P) and whose trace is equal to the number of particles (tr(P) = N e).",
    "The energy expectation value of a Slater determinant can be evaluated using Wick's theoremE[P] = ⟨Ψ| Ĥ |Ψ⟩ = ab T ab P ba + 1 2 abcd (V ac,bd -V ac,db)P ba P dc.",
    "(31)We define the Hartree-Fock Hamiltonian 25[H HF [P]] ab = T ab + cd (V ac,bd -V ac,db)P dc,(32)allowing us to rewrite the energy functional asE[P] = 1 2 tr T + H HF [P] P.(33)It will be useful to also define the Hartree and Fock contributions toH HF [P] separately [H H [P]] ab = cd V ac,bd P dc (34) [H F [P]] ab = - cd V ac,db P dc.",
    "(35)In terms of these, the energy functional can be written as 26E[P] = tr(T P) + 1 2 tr (H H [P] + H F [P])P. (36)It can be shown that, for P to correspond to a local minimum of E[P] within the variational manifold of N e -particle Slater determinants, a necessary condition is that P be given by occupying the N e lowest-energy eigenstates of H HF [P] (this is known as the \"aufbau principle\" analogous to atomic physics) [212].",
    "This self-consistency condition is the basis for the iterative Hartree-Fock optimization procedure that we outline next."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "(35)In terms of these, the energy functional can be written as 26E[P] = tr(T P) + 1 2 tr (H H [P] + H F [P])P. (36)It can be shown that, for P to correspond to a local minimum of E[P] within the variational manifold of N e -particle Slater determinants, a necessary condition is that P be given by occupying the N e lowest-energy eigenstates of H HF [P] (this is known as the \"aufbau principle\" analogous to atomic physics) [212]."
